'''Saint Eunan's College''' ({{lang-ga|Col<U+00E1>iste Adhamhn<U+00E1>in}}) is an all-male voluntary [[Secondary education|secondary school]]. Located in Glencar, [[Letterkenny]], [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], the building is a three-storey castle with four round towers at each corner of the building. The school is named after the [[Abbot of Iona]] [[Eunan|Saint Eunan]], a native of Donegal and [[patron saint]] of the [[Diocese of Raphoe (Roman Catholic)|Diocese of Raphoe]]. The college celebrated its [[centenary]] in 2006.<ref>[http://www.sainteunans.com/history.htm Information and References], Saint Eunan's College website. (accessed 2008-07-06)</ref>

==History==
Saint Eunan's College was founded as a [[boarding school]] in 1906 by the then [[Diocese of Raphoe (Roman Catholic)|Bishop of Raphoe]], [[Patrick O'Donnell (cardinal)|Patrick O' Donnell]]. Originally intended as a [[seminary|minor seminary]], it was designed to prepare students for the [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[priesthood]]. Diocesan colleges became an increasingly popular feature at the time and were designed to give the best possible [[Catholic]] education to boys of every class.
[[File:College Letterkenny Eunan.jpg|right|thumb|400px|Saint Eunan's College]]

The student population expanded in the 1920s and it was necessary to build a new extension to the College in the early 1930s. The current recreation hall was built in 1958 and the science block in 1968. The College Chapel was designed by J.J. Robinson, the architect of [[Galway Cathedral]]. It was completed in 1961 at a cost of <U+00A3>42,000.<ref>''Did You Know'', Published in the 1995 edition of the Letterkenny and District Christmas Annual</ref>

The 'new building' was opened in 1979 to cater for the 500 students enrolled at the time. Due to the growth of other second level schools in the area the number of boarders dropped extensively and in 1992, the boarding wing was finally shut down. Saint Eunan's College continues to this day as a Catholic School under the trusteeship of the Bishop of [[Raphoe]].

The school currently serves approximately 900 students from Letterkenny and its surrounding area, and is one of the few remaining all-male schools in the north-western part of [[Ireland]]. The president, since 2009, is Christopher Darby and the vice [[Principal (school)|principal]], since 2010, is Mary Cunningham.

In 2007, the school came to the attention of the national media. Retailers were urged not to sell eggs and flour to students following a spate of attacks on passing cars.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/national-news/garda-crackdown-on-bad-eggs-in-rural-town-61690.html Irish Independent - Garda crackdown on 'bad eggs' in rural town]</ref>

In 2009, Christopher Darby became the first lay person to become president of the college, taking over from Father Michael Carney.<ref>[http://www.donegaldemocrat.ie/donegalnews/New-president-for-St-Eunan39s.5423522.jp New president for St Eunan's College], Donegal Democrat, 2 July 2009</ref>

===Allegations of child abuse===
In his autobiography which was released in 2010, internationally renowned chef [[Conrad Gallagher]] told of the abuse he received at the college. He discussed how the [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] would feel him up and attempt to interfere with him. However he has decided not to press charges against the abusers. He stated that he wishes to put it all behind him. However, St Eunan's is not a Christian Brothers school, which casts some doubt on this statement.<ref>[http://www.silobreaker.com/chefs-bitter-taste-of-st-eunans-revealed-in-new-book-5_2263970584918491196 Chef's bitter taste of St Eunan's revealed in new book], Donegal Democrat, December 2010</ref>

==Centenary celebrations==
Centenary celebrations began on Friday 6 October 2006 with an exhibition of photographs and the launch of the centenary booklet. The photographic exhibition included photographs from down through the years. It included photos of past and present staff and students as well as sports teams from the past one hundred years. Books, uniforms and other memorabilia were on display. The exhibition was opened by [[S<U+00E9>amus Hegarty]], Bishop of Derry, a past student and a former patron of the school. On Saturday a sporting exhibition took place on the pitch. A veterans soccer match was organised along with a veterans gaelic football match. Mass was celebrated on Sunday by [[Philip Boyce]], [[Bishop of Raphoe]] in [[Cathedral of St. Eunan and St. Columba|St. Eunan's Cathedral]]. A dinner dance was held in the ''Mount Errigal Hotel'' later that evening.<ref>[http://archives.nwipp-newspapers.com/archive_detail.php?archiveFile=2006/September/22/GeneralNews/7122.xml&start=0&numPer=20&keyword=St+Eunans+College&sectionSearch=&begindate=1%2F1%2F2003&enddate=10%2F17%2F2008&authorSearch=&IncludeStories=1&pubsection=&page=&IncludePages=1&IncludeImages=1&mode=allwords&archive_pubname=Donegal+News%0A%09%09%09 Plans for St Eunan's College Centenary celebrations], Donegal News, September 22, 2006</ref>

On Sunday 8 April 2007, golfer [[Paul McGinley]] launched the College Centenary Golf Classic. It was the final event in the centenary year celebrations and was played at [[Letterkenny Golf Club]].<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/sport/golf/college-backed-by-mcginleys-44076.html College backed by McGinleys], Irish Independent, April 18, 2007</ref>

